<main class="article-container" id="article">
<div class="above-article">
    <div class="ad-wrapper ad-topboxrightphoto-wrapper">
        <div class="ad" id="ad-topboxrightphoto"></div>
    </div>
    <div id="article-header">
        <ul class="metadata">
            <li class="kicker">In Focus</li>
            <li class="date">Oct 4, 2013</li>
            <li class="num-photos">40 Photos</li>
        </ul>
        <h1 class="hed">The Broken Lives of Fukushima</h1>
        <div class="byline"><a href="/alan-taylor/" title="Alan Taylor">Alan Taylor</a></div>

        <div id="article-content">
            <p>More than two and a half years have passed since the massive 2011 earthquake and tsunami struck northeastern Japan, wrecking the Fukushima nuclear plant and claiming nearly 16,000 lives. When it became clear that nuclear contamination was widespread, the government evacuated about 160,000 people living near the plant and established a 20-km compulsory exclusion zone, which remains in place today. Today, Tokyo Electric Power Company is still struggling to contain contaminated water at the destroyed plant. Former residents are allowed to return up to once a month, but they're forbidden to stay overnight. Reuters photographer Damir Sagolj recently joined one of these trips, capturing images of a haunting landscape and lives torn apart by disaster.</p>
        </div>
        <a href="#" class="read-more">Read more</a>
        


