        </figure>
        <div class="mobile-caption-wrapper">
            <p class="caption">
                Plastic bags, containing radiated soil, leaves and debris from a decontamination operation, sit dumped at a tennis court at a sports park in Naraha town, on September 21, 2013. The most ambitious radiation clean-up ever attempted has proved costly, complex and time-consuming since the Japanese government began it more than two years ago in the wake of the Fukushima nuclear meltdown. It may also fail -- storage is a big problem. Most of the contaminated soil and leaves remain piled up in driveways and empty lots because of fierce opposition from local communities to storing it in one place until the Ministry of Environment secures a central site that could hold it for the longer term.
                <a class="permalink" href="/photo/2013/10/the-broken-lives-of-fukushima/100603/#img36">#</a>
            </p>
            <div class="credit">
                
                
                Reuters/Damir Sagolj
                
